comments.Date_first_released: In Germany. The specific release date is unclear. 26 March is an estimate. Walter Everett, Barry Miles, Kenneth Womack, and Margotin & Guesdon all say 5 March 1964 for the West German release (though Womack and M&G cite Everett). If you read Mark Lewisohn and John C. Winn however, they write that the songs were mixed for mono and stereo on 10 and 12 March 1964, respectively, then sent to West Germany and America for release. Winn adds that after mixing they were “sent to West Germany for rush-release…”, but he does not provide a date. Looking at the official German charts, it says both songs first entered the charts the week of 1 April 1964. I have not been able to narrow the timeline any narrower than this, with release happening somewhere between 12 March – 1 April 1964. I guess the best we can say is late-March.

comments.Key_varispeeded:
Lovely Rita's vocals were recorded at 46.5 cycles instead of the usual 50, so they're slightly sped up.
George Martin said that the piano solo was recorded at 41.25 cycles, thus 3 semitones flat.
The multitrack of the whole piece was then played at 48.75 cycles as they mixed it.

I'm guessing the song was originally recorded in E, but would seem to be about a quarter tone flat on the record. I'm not sure why George would have dropped the song down into C# for his solo, except for the timbral effect that came from speeding it up. It certainly wasn't done to make the solo easier to play.

And there are also some speed variations between mono and stereo - Lucy in the Sky and Lovely Rita are both a bit faster in stereo

comments.Performer_RG_John: There is uncertainty and disagreement about who played which instruments on this song. The book by Kevin Howlett with the Abbey Road Deluxe Edition disagrees with Lewisohn (1988), and there are many opinions expressed online. comments.Performer_drums_Ringo:
Here is a comment by David Harvey from the Beatles Bible web site, which I agree with. 
"It has been claimed that Paul played drums. However, Paul himself admits that he can play 4/4 on the drums, but not shuffles, and not all the line-ups in Kevin Howlett’s books are 100% correct as a result of either him or Giles Martin (who wasn’t even born when these recordings were made) making mistakes or omitting certain contributions.
It’s okay to have differing opinions and I respect that, but sometimes, it’s a good idea to trust our ears.
This webpage – http://www.beatlesebooks.com/old-brown-shoe?sitecookie=46cd9c17fee32bfe9fe45da4d79b7234 – also indicates that it’s very likely to be Ringo on drums and has the quote from Paul himself about his inability to play drum shuffles not to mention that Ringo had been developing the shuffle beat as far back as the Twickenham sessions of January 1969."
